statement.p:
In , we considered the equation x-2y=3 for a line in the plane. Setting parameter y=t and isolating x in this equation leads to general solution

	\uvec{x}
	= \begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix} 3+2t \\ t \end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}.

Geometrically, the vector \uvec{x}_0 = (3,0) represents an initial point on the line, and algebraically represents the particular solution to the system obtained from parameter value t=0. The vector \uvec{p} = (2,1) represents a vector parallel to the line, and every other point on the line ( every other solution to the system) can be obtained by adding a scalar multiple of \uvec{p} to \uvec{x}_0. For example, the point \uvec{x} = (4,1/2) lies on the line, as we can verify by checking
 4 - 2\cdot\frac{1}{2} = 4-1 = 3, 
so that the coordinates of the point satisfy the line equation x-2y=3. We can solve for t in the vector equation
 \begin{bmatrix}4\\\frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}3\\0\end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix} 
to see exactly how this point is a multiple of \uvec{p} away from \uvec{x}_0:

	\begin{bmatrix}4\\\frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}3\\0\end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix}1\\\frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix}2t\\t\end{bmatrix}
	\qquad\qquad\implies\qquad\qquad
	t=\frac{1}{2}.

When we have just a single plane in space, as in , we can view its equation as a system of equations, just as we did with the line in
.
In this activity, we worked with equation x-y+2z=-3. In this case, we will need two parameters to express the general solution, and each parameter will provide us with a vector parallel to the plane. Setting y=s and z=t and solving, we get

	\uvec{x}
	= \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}
	= \begin{bmatrix} -3+s-2t \\ s \\ t \end{bmatrix}
	= \left[\begin{array}{r} -3 \\ 0 \\0 \end{array}\right]
	+ s\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	+ t\left[\begin{array}{r} -2 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right].

Here, the initial point on the plane is \uvec{x}_0 = (-3,0,0), which corresponds to parameter values s=t=0. Every other point on the plane corresponds to other choices of parameter values. For example, as in the activity, the point (-1,4,1) is on the plane. We can verify this by checking
 -1 - 4 + 2\cdot 1 = -3, 
so that the coordinates of the point satisfy the plane equation x-y+2z=-3. We can also describe this point using the vector equation \uvec{x} = \uvec{x}_0 + s\uvec{p}_1 + t\uvec{p}_2:

	\left[\begin{array}{r} -1 \\ 4 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]
	= \left[\begin{array}{r} -3 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]
	+ s\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	+ t\left[\begin{array}{r} -2 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{array}\right].

Solving this vector equation for s and t leads to a  system of linear equations!

	\left[\begin{array}{r} -1 \\ 4 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]
	-
	\left[\begin{array}{r} -3 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{array}\right]
	\amp = \begin{bmatrix} s \\ s \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
	+ \begin{bmatrix} -2t \\ 0 \\ t \end{bmatrix}
	\\
	\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\amp= \begin{bmatrix} s-2t \\ s \\ t \end{bmatrix}.

From the second and third coordinates we immmediately see s=4 and t=1, and we also verify that s-2t = 2 for these parameter values, to satisfy the equality of the first coordinates on right and left.

In , we again want to determine the point of intersection (if any) of a line and a plane, but this time both line and plane are described by vector equations. But if a point lies on both line and plane, its coordinates must have a simultaneous description by both vector equations in terms of parameters:


		\uvec{x}
		\amp
		= \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}
		= \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + t \left[\begin{array}{r} -1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]
		= \begin{bmatrix} 2-t \\ t \\ 3+t \end{bmatrix},

		\uvec{x}
		\amp
		= \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}
		= \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
		+ r\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
		+ s\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
		= \begin{bmatrix} 3+r+3s \\ 1+r \\ r+2s \end{bmatrix}.


Now, this point can only have one set of coordinates, so these two descriptions must actually be the same. This lets us set up a  system of linear equations!

	\begin{array}{rcl}
		x\colon \amp \qquad \amp 2-t = 3+r+3s\text{,} \\
		y\colon \amp \qquad \amp t = 1+r\text{,} \\
		z\colon \amp \qquad \amp 3+t=r+2s\text{,}
	\end{array}
	\qquad\implies\qquad
	\left\{\begin{array}{rcrcrcr}
		r \amp + \amp 3 s \amp + \amp t \amp = \amp -1\text{,} \\
		r \amp \amp \amp - \amp t \amp = \amp -1\text{,} \\
		r \amp + \amp 2s \amp - \amp t \amp = \amp 3\text{.}
	\end{array}\right.

We could put this system in a matrix and row reduce, but we only really care about the value of parameter t in the solution, because knowing t allows us to determine \uvec{x} from the vector description for the line. So we can use Cramer's rule instead. Write A for the coefficient matrix of this system, and A_3 for the matrix obtained by replacing the third column of A by the vector of contants. Then,


		\det A_3
		\amp=
		\left\lvert\begin{array}{rrr}
			1 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
			1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
			1 \amp 2 \amp 3
		\end{array}\right\rvert
		= -12,

		\det A
		\amp=
		\left\lvert\begin{array}{rrr}
			1 \amp 3 \amp 1 \\
			1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
			1 \amp 2 \amp -1
		\end{array}\right\rvert
		= 4

		\implies \quad
		t \amp= \frac{\det A_3}{\det A} = -3.


Now that we have t=-3, we can determine the point of intersection:

	\uvec{x}
	= \begin{bmatrix} 2-t \\ t \\ 3+t \end{bmatrix}
	= \left[\begin{array}{r} 5 \\ -3 \\ 0 \end{array}\right].
